data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.uscc.gov%2Fsites%2Fdefault%2Ffiles%2FAnnual_Report%2FChapters%2FChapter%25203%2520Section%25204-%2520China%2520and%2520Hong%2520Kong_0.pdf&d=pjepta7IDo9He3ZZvGfzZ7%2BHiWCy6q6AsXO%2BLNmzhis%3D&h=9a635d98\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.uscc.gov/sites/default/files/Annual_Report/Chapters/Chapter%203%20Section%204-%20China%20and%20Hong%20Kong_0.pdf</a><br />\nThe Commission recommends: <br />\n&bull; Congress direct the U.S. Department of Commerce and other relevant government agencies to prepare an unclassified public report, with a classified annex, examining and assessing the adequacy of U.S. export control policy for dual-use technology as it relates to U.S. treatment of Hong Kong and China as separate customs areas.<br />\n<br />\n&bull; Congressional interparliamentary groups engage parliamentarians from the United Kingdom, EU, and Taiwan in a biennial review of China&rsquo;s adherence to the Basic Law, with specific attention to rule of law, freedom of speech and assembly, and press freedom, and issue a report based on its findings after each review.<br />\n<br />\n&bull; Members of Congress participate in congressional delegations to Hong Kong and meet with Hong Kong officials, prodemocracy legislators, civil society, and business representatives in the territory and when they visit the United States. In meetings with Hong Kong and Chinese officials, they should raise concerns about Beijing&rsquo;s adherence to the &ldquo;one country, two systems&rdquo; policy and China&rsquo;s promise to allow Hong Kong a &ldquo;high degree of autonomy.&rdquo; They should also continue to express support for freedom of expression and rule of law in Hong Kong."},{"pid":"c1acee50e949573b2835a9271af7d46c393d3091","tid":901961,"uid":68118,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2018-11-14T16:22:50.000Z","msg":"不用怕 我們還有黨啊"},{"pid":"1632cf0b263b3a71f36cc59f570202405ce96c27","tid":901961,"uid":36238,"like":0,"